Abstract

Energy is a concept with a wide definition range. We use and need many types of energy in daily life. As we all know, energy sources are not endless and will run out one day. Therefore, countries take different steps on issues such as energy saving and energy production. In this report, Izmirâs electrical energy production and chemical energy consumption datasets are analyzed. According to these analyses, the energy consumption of certain tram/metro stations in Izmir differ from each other. In the HarmandalÄ± Electricity generation dataset, the differences between the planned and produced electrical energy were examined.

Confidence Interval

Dataset 1:

mean(enerji.tuketimi.yolcubasina$IZMIR_METRO)
## [1] 1
sd(enerji.tuketimi.yolcubasina$IZMIR_METRO)
## [1] 0.4340716
norm.interval = function(data, variance, conf.level = 0.95) {
   z = qnorm((1 - conf.level)/2, lower.tail = FALSE)
   xbar = mean(data)
   sdx = sqrt(variance/length(data))
   c(xbar - z * sdx, xbar + z * sdx)
}

norm.interval(enerji.tuketimi.yolcubasina$IZMIR_METRO, variance=var(enerji.tuketimi.yolcubasina$IZMIR_METRO), conf.level = 0.95)
## [1] 0.7544054 1.2455946

The output on the above is confidenece interval of the data.A point estimate for the true mean energy consumption in the per passanger is 1.0, and we are 95% confident that the true mean is between 0.724204 kWh and 1.275796 kWh.

Hypothesis Testing

Dataset 1:

Hypothesis 1: enerji.tuketimi.yolcubasina.IZMIR_METRO mean is different than 2 kWh, Ho:mu=2 Ha:mu < 2 kWh

enerji.tuketimi.yolcubasina.t.test<- t.test(enerji.tuketimi.yolcubasina$IZMIR_METRO, alternative = c("two.sided"), mu = 2, conf.level = 0.95)
enerji.tuketimi.yolcubasina.t.test
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  enerji.tuketimi.yolcubasina$IZMIR_METRO
## t = -7.9805, df = 11, p-value = 6.686e-06
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 2
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.724204 1.275796
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
##         1

Result of t test is -7.9805. When p value is less than alpha, we reject the hypothesis. P-value ~ 0.006. Thatâs mean p value is less than alpha(0.5) So, we reject h0 hypothesis.

Hypothesis: The mean sepal width for the Versicolor species is estimated to be less than for the Virginica species.

iris.t.test <- t.test(SepalLengthCm~ Species, Iris, Species %in% c("Iris-versicolor", "Iris-virginica"), var.equal = T)
iris.t.test
## 
##  Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  SepalLengthCm by Species
## t = -5.6292, df = 98, p-value = 1.725e-07
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group Iris-versicolor and group Iris-virginica is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.8818516 -0.4221484
## sample estimates:
## mean in group Iris-versicolor  mean in group Iris-virginica 
##                         5.936                         6.588

The p-value is less than the significance level of so we can reject the null hypothesis.

Data Normality:

with(Iris, qqnorm(SepalLengthCm[Species=="Iris-versicolor"]))
with(Iris, qqline(SepalLengthCm[Species=="Iris-versicolor"], col = "red"))

In this data the points to close to lying on a straight line. So we can say Iris data is normal.

ANOVA / REGRESSÄ°ON

Dataset 1: H0: There is no difference between the means. (ANOVA)
